{
  "texts": [
    "In PEFT settings, only a small fraction of model parameters are updated, which makes it crucial to allocate gradient updates effectively to maximize the impact of limited trainable capacity.",
    "Incorporating reward weights into the supervised loss allows the fine-tuning process to emphasize semantically important tokens-such as correct answers in multiple-choice QA, key reasoning steps in chain-of-thought tasks, or factual spans in scientific text-so that the model can learn from the most informative parts of the data.Reward-weighted learning introduces a form of fine-grained adaptivity at the token level, complementing rank-level adaptation mechanisms.",
    "This approach accelerates convergence, improves reasoning accuracy, and makes better use of small compute budgets.",
    "In resource-constrained scenarios (such as LoRA or QLoRA training on 4/8-bit hardware), reward-weighted learning enables the model to focus limited updates on the parts of the input that matter most, leading to superior generalization and robustness without increasing the overall parameter count.",
    "Mathematical formulation.Formally, for a sequence of tokens x = (x 1,..., x T) with labels y t, we modify the standard cross-entropy loss L by introducing reward weights w t:L = 1 T T ∑ t=1 w t • CE(z t, y t),where z t are the model logits and w t > 1 for tokens that are semantically critical (e.g., final answers or key reasoning steps)."
  ]
}